               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320405-320-person2651">
                  WILLIAM 
                  MILLER
               <interp inst="t18320405-320-person2651" type="surname" value="MILLER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320405-320-person2651" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320405-320-person2651" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am employed on board a ship. I met the prisoner on <placeName id="t18320405-320-crimeloc1856">London-bridge</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18320405-320-crimeloc1856" type="placeName" value="London-bridge"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18320405-320-crimeloc1856" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320405-320-off1854 t18320405-320-crimeloc1856"></join> on the night of the 25th of February, a little before nine o'clock; we went into the Redcross, and sat some time - we came out towards the bridge again; we then went under one of the arches of the bridge - we staid there some time, and then she said she rather expected there was a Policeman at the corner; she went to see - I then missed my watch out of my pocket: I went out, but did not see her - I went on till I saw a watchman, and told him the case - he told me to go the Policeman; I am sure my watch had not fallen out.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. PHILLIPS. Q. I believe you had not much money? A. I had 25s. or 26s.; I had not paid her any thing - I was to have paid her, and should if she had not gone away - I did not give her my watch; it had no case to it - I was to have given her 1s. and something to drink; I might be a little the worse for drink - I cannot say how much I drank: I might be two hours in the public-house - I had pawned the case of my watch.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320405-320-person2652">
                  JAMES 
                  LAWSON
               <interp inst="t18320405-320-person2652" type="surname" value="LAWSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320405-320-person2652" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320405-320-person2652" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a pawnbroker. The prisoner brought this watch on Monday morning, and wanted to pawn it - she said she had found it on London-bridge; I asked where the case was - she said her husband had broken it, and it was gone to be repaired; my lad then put a paper into my hand, that such a watch had been stolen - the prisoner said she would fetch her husband, and ran out; I pursued and took her.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18320405-320-verdict1857" type="verdictDescription">
